Title : Howard Beck
Text : '''Howard “What Up Beck” Beck''' (born July 6, 1968 in [[Oakland, California]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/learning/students/ask_reporters/Howard_Beck.html|title=Ask a Reporter Q&A: Howard Beck |date=2007|publisher=The New York Times |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091015031713/http://nytimes.com/learning/students/ask_reporters/Howard_Beck.html |archive-date=October 15, 2009|dead-url=yes}}</ref>)  is an [[United States|American]] sports journalist.  Described as "highly regarded" by [[USA Today]],<ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/business/2013/11/12/stelter-joins-cnn/3505131/ 'N.Y. Times' loses 2 more top writers to TV, online]</ref>  Beck has covered the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) for the [[Los Angeles Daily News]],<ref>[http://www.complex.com/sports/2014/07/ranking-the-most-popular-nba-writers-and-their-sources/howard-beck Complex - Ranking the Most Popular NBA Writers and Their Sources]</ref> the [[New York Times]]<ref>[http://topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/b/howard_beck/index.html]</ref> and currently [[Bleacher Report]].<ref>[http://bleacherreport.com/users/3065513-howard-beck]</ref>

At the Los Angeles Daily News, Howard covered the [[Los Angeles Lakers]]. With the New York Times, Howard covered the [[New York Knicks]] for most of his tenure with a brief assignment to the [[Brooklyn Nets]] during their first season in Brooklyn.<ref>[http://nymag.com/daily/sports/2012/06/new-york-nba-beat-is-shifting.html New York - The New York NBA Beat Is Shifting]</ref> In the fall of 2013 Howard left the New York Times for the Bleacher Report to be their national NBA writer.<ref>[https://newrepublic.com/article/114777/bleacher-report-hires-new-york-times-nba-writer-howard-beck New Republic - Another NYT Writer Leaves for a Web Upstart, But That's Not the Real Story Here]</ref><ref>[http://deadspin.com/why-howard-beck-left-the-new-york-times-for-bleacher-re-1349408343  Deadspin - Why Howard Beck Left The New York Times For Bleacher Report]</ref>

Beginning in 2017, Howard created and hosts The Full 48 podcast. Guests have included NBA commissioner Adam Silver, Actor, Kelly Aucoin, LA Lakers owner Jeanie Buss, Counting Crows lead singer, Adam Duritz and others.[https://player.fm/series/the-full-48]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://player.fm/series/the-full-48|title=The Full 48|last=FM|first=Player|website=The Full 48|language=en|access-date=2018-08-01}}</ref>

Howard was raised in California and graduated from the [[University of California, Davis]]<ref>[http://thebiglead.com/2012/06/17/an-interview-with-howard-beck-of-the-new-york-times/ The Big Lead - An Interview with Howard Beck of the New York Times]</ref> where he served as editor in chief for the California Aggie newspaper. He currently resides in [[Brooklyn]], New York.

